{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"87763d4b-41ac-4b1e-942c-004abfbce577","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet-tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect the trace:**\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect for ~30 seconds (adjust as needed)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in:\n- **Visual Studio** (Windows) — best experience\n- **Speedscope** (https://speedscope.app) — cross-platform, browser-based\n- Convert to `.speedscope.json`: `dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope`\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or the `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` env var with `dotnet-dsrouter` from a debug container.\n- For production, consider `--buffersize 256` to reduce overhead.\n- `perf` is an alternative if you need OS-level (native) call stacks, but `dotnet-trace` is simpler and .NET-aware.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a4bae2ca-6509-43a8-be21-0466e5df0730","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":454,"requestId":"9816:11A36E:CCAF31:EDDB79:69F40213"},"id":"283cf400-fba9-41b8-9af9-e9a366006117","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:30:06.251Z","parentId":"e508601b-05fc-4cbb-9a6e-3df38e00b567"}
